        "summary":  "AWS examined how leading engineering teams are achieving 4.5x to 10x productivity gains by restructuring entire workflows around AI rather than adding AI tools to existing processes. Three Amazon case studies show: Bedrock\u0027s infrastructure team completing an 18-month project in 76 days, Prime Video\u0027s financial systems team compressing 90 weeks to 24 weeks, and Amazon Stores piloting the approach across 50+ teams. Five critical practices emerge: investing in agent context, accepting an initial slowdown period, maintaining well-scoped task backlogs, defining clear requirements before code generation, and shifting testing responsibilities to agents.",
        "execSummary":  "This piece is essential reading for enterprise technology leaders because it reframes AI adoption from a tooling question to a workflow redesign question ΓÇö the 4.5x to 10x gains come from restructuring how teams work, not from using better AI tools on unchanged processes. The Amazon Bedrock team\u0027s 76-day completion of an 18-month project is the headline number, but the more actionable insight is the five practices that separate frontier teams from average adopters, particularly the counterintuitive \u0027accept an initial slowdown period\u0027 before gains materialize. For customer-support and operations leaders, the principle of shifting testing responsibilities to agents has direct applicability to QA, compliance verification, and case-quality assurance workflows. The caveat is that all three case studies are internal Amazon examples on Amazon\u0027s own infrastructure, so external generalizability should be validated with independent benchmarks before organizational restructuring decisions are made.",
