        "summary":  "The article argues that as AI systems transition from generating recommendations to making autonomous business decisions, organizations must shift from accepting \u0027black-box\u0027 AI to implementing \u0027glass-box\u0027 AI with full observability. The author contends that \u0027the model decided\u0027 is no longer acceptable when AI systems approve transactions, route shipments, and trigger actions with minimal human oversight, making transparency and auditability essential for governance and accountability.",
        "execSummary":  "As agentic AI moves from advisory to autonomous ΓÇö approving transactions, routing orders, triggering workflows ΓÇö the \u0027black box\u0027 defense disappears and organizations become accountable for every decision the model makes. This is the central governance challenge of the current AI wave: enterprises need observability stacks, audit trails, and explainability layers before deploying autonomous AI in any customer-facing or regulated process. For customer-support leaders in particular, this has direct implications: AI-handled escalations and resolutions must be auditable. The caveat is that most current AI platforms lack native glass-box tooling, meaning custom observability investment is required.",
